  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Pete Crow-Armstrong walks off Giants in Ten Innings",
    "subheadline": "Pete Crow-Armstrong's Two-Homer Effort Powers Cubs to 10th-Inning Victory",
    "lead_angle": "Pete Crow-Armstrong sent the Wrigley Field faithful into a frenzy with a tenth-inning single, plating the winning run and securing a 3-2 walk-off victory for the Chicago Cubs over the San Francisco Giants. Crow-Armstrong's heroics concluded a taut battle where the Cubs, facing defeat, rallied late. Ryan Rolison earned the win in relief for Chicago, while Sam Hentges took the loss for San Francisco after surrendering the deciding hit.\n\nThe ninth inning brought the game's turning point. San Francisco Giants broke a 1-1 tie, taking a one-run lead. But the Chicago Cubs quickly answered in their half, pushing the tying run across with bases loaded, sending the contest into extra frames and setting the stage for the dramatic finish.\n\nCrow-Armstrong’s bat proved irrepressible throughout the afternoon. He ripped two home runs earlier in the game, demonstrating power and clutch hitting that culminated in his game-winning RBI. His 4-for-5 effort, including those two blasts and two runs batted in, carried the Chicago offense. This hard-fought win at home provides a critical boost for the Cubs, solidifying their standing in the division race against a formidable National League opponent.",
    "reason": "Extra-inning walk-off — the purest combination of tension and resolution the sport offers."
